138029","align":"alignnone","width":"1999"},"children":[{"type":"tag","name":"img","attribs":{"class":"size-full wp-image-138029","src":"https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/image5.png","alt":"A screenshot of the YXTDZ which is a cheap copy of a car booster seat.","width":"1999","height":"1044","noInlineStyles":false},"children":[],"dbData":{"width":1999,"height":1044,"sources":[{"path":"2020/02/image5-300x157.png","width":300,"height":157},{"path":"2020/02/image5-1024x535.png","width":1024,"height":535},{"path":"2020/02/image5-768x401.png","width":768,"height":401},{"path":"2020/02/image5-1536x802.png","width":1536,"height":802}]}},{"data":" The YXTDZ is a cheap copy of a car booster seat called the Mifold, but without the safety labeling or documentation that it meets federal standards.","type":"text"}],"dbData":{"credit":null}},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"Copies like the YXTDZ lack the clear labeling and safety test results of the compliant Mifold (Sumroy compares his invention to cheap knockoffs ","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"a","attribs":{"href":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZWeLhWxQbMo\u0026feature=youtu.be","rel":"noopener noreferrer","target":"_blank"},"children":[{"data":"in this video","type":"text"}]},{"data":"). The physical distinctions between the products are clear, but the invisible differences are far more worrisome. And because Sumroy is faced with a knockoff rather than a counterfeit, Amazon’s anti-counterfeiting tools can’t be used to combat the problem.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"We reached out to Amazon about this product. The ","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"a","attribs":{"href":"https://wrctr.co/37Gcxj3","rel":"noopener noreferrer","target":"_blank"},"children":[{"data":"YXTDZ storefront","type":"text"}]},{"data":" still exists, but it is no longer offering the car booster seat on Amazon.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"h3","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"The third-party seller system: a boon to counterfeiters","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"Counterfeits have always been an issue. But the Internet has exacerbated the problem.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"In the brick-and-mortar days, a counterfeit product might have a harder time getting onto the shelves of a legitimate business, since it would be in a retailer’s best interest to vet the validity and safety of products the retailer might be liable for selling to a customer. Business owners were gatekeepers, and counterfeits were largely relegated to back alleys, figuratively and literally.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"Things are different online. Smaller vendors who peddle counterfeits, particularly pseudonymous third-party sellers on e-commerce platforms with broad reach and trust, now have access to millions of customers they never had when they were lurking in downtown alleys and flea markets. “The rise of e-commerce has led to the rise in counterfeits,” says Kim Gianopoulos, director of a Government Accountability Office (GAO) team that investigated counterfeits for sale online.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"If you shop on Amazon, you’ve probably bought things from third-party sellers without knowing it. I have. Third-party sellers now dominate Amazon sales, accounting for ","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"a","attribs":{"href":"https://statista.com/statistics/259782/third-party-seller-share-of-amazon-platform/","rel":"noopener noreferrer","target":"_blank"},"children":[{"data":"54 percent of units sold on Amazon in the second quarter of 2019","type":"text"}]},{"data":", according to Statista. “Third-party sellers are kicking our first-party butt,” Amazon CEO Jeff Bezos told shareholders in a ","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"a","attribs":{"href":"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1018724/000119312519103013/d727605dex991.htm","rel":"noopener noreferrer","target":"_blank"},"children":[{"data":"2019 letter","type":"text"}]},{"data":", calling the increase—from 3 percent of sales in 2000 to over half today—“remarkable.” Annual third-party sales have grown to a whopping $160 billion.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"shortcode-pullquote","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"You’ve probably bought things from third-party sellers without knowing it. I have.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"Making things particularly tricky is the fact that a single e-commerce product page may include offerings from the manufacturer as well as from many third-party sellers, some honest and some not so honest. On an e-commerce site, it’s as though those back-alley and swap-meet sellers have gotten to put their wares inside the store, on the same shelf as the real goods. And product placement relies on an algorithm that can push the cheapest version to the front of the shelf.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"This would be fine if all third-party sellers were committed to honest sales of authentic goods. And it’s important to note again that many third-party sellers are upstanding. But with so many sellers competing for clicks, one way to win the customer is by offering the lowest price, and it’s often easier to bring the price down if you’re selling a counterfeit.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"At Wirecutter, we’ve seen this problem pop up with ","type":"text"},{"type":"tag"